    public abstract class DialogWrapper
extends java.lang.Object
    The standard base class for modal dialog boxes. The dialog wrapper could be used only on event dispatch thread. In case when the dialog must be created from other threads use EventQueue.invokeLater(Runnable) or EventQueue.invokeAndWait(Runnable).
    See Also:
    DialogWrapper on SDK DevGuide

    • Constructor Detail

      • DialogWrapper

        protected DialogWrapper(Project project,
                        boolean canBeParent)
        Creates modal DialogWrapper. The currently active window will be the dialog's parent.
        Parameters:
        project - parent window for the dialog will be calculated based on focused window for the specified project. This parameter can be null. In this case parent window will be suggested based on current focused window.
        canBeParent - specifies whether the dialog can be parent for other windows. This parameter is used by WindowManager.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalStateException - if the dialog is invoked not on the event dispatch thread

      • DialogWrapper

        @Deprecated
protected DialogWrapper(boolean canBeParent,
                        boolean applicationModalIfPossible)
        Deprecated. use DialogWrapper(Project, boolean, boolean)
        Typically, we should set a parent explicitly. Use WindowManager.suggestParentWindow(com.intellij.openapi.project.Project) method to find out the best parent for your dialog. Exceptions are cases when we do not have a project to figure out which window is more suitable as an owner for the dialog.

        protected abstract javax.swing.JComponent createCenterPanel()

      • doCancelAction

        public void doCancelAction()
        This method is invoked by default implementation of "Cancel" action. It just closes dialog with CANCEL_EXIT_CODE. This is convenient place to override functionality of "Cancel" action. Note that the method does nothing if "Cancel" action isn't enabled.

      • doCancelAction

        public void doCancelAction(java.awt.AWTEvent source)
        You can use this method if you want to know by which event this actions got triggered. It is called only if the cancel action was triggered by some input event, doCancelAction is called otherwise.
        Parameters:
        source - AWT event
        See Also:
        doCancelAction()

      • doOKAction

        protected void doOKAction()
        This method is invoked by default implementation of "OK" action. It just closes dialog with OK_EXIT_CODE. This is convenient place to override functionality of "OK" action. Note that the method does nothing if "OK" action isn't enabled.

      • createActions

        protected javax.swing.Action [] createActions()
        Creates actions for dialog.

        By default "OK" and "Cancel" actions are returned. The "Help" action is automatically added if getHelpId() returns non-null value.

        Each action is represented by JButton created by createJButtonForAction(Action). These buttons are then placed into south panel of dialog.

        Returns:
        dialog actions
        See Also:
        createSouthPanel(), createJButtonForAction(javax.swing.Action)

      • setErrorText

        protected void setErrorText(java.lang.String text)
        Don't override this method. It is not final for the API compatibility. It will not be called by the DialogWrapper's validator. Use this method only in circumstances when the exact invalid component is hard to detect or the valid status is based on several fields. In other cases use setErrorText(String, JComponent) method.
        Parameters:
        text - the error text to display
